Japan, Thailand, China, Malaysia, Taiwan: Asia Bond and Currency Preview

-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 
2011-03-08T22:33:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/japan-thailand-china-malaysia-taiwan-asia-bond-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will have media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  Toyota Motor Corp.’s President Akio Toyoda will present the
company’s “Global Vision 2020” plan at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will announce at 10:30 a.m. in
Tokyo the amount of 20-year Japanese  government bonds  it plans
to sell on March 16.  The Cabinet Office will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on machinery orders for January. Orders rose 3 percent in
January from December, when they increased 1.7 percent,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was at 1.295 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 82.67 per dollar at 7:27 a.m. in Tokyo.    Thailand : The central bank will raise the benchmark
interest rate by 25 basis points to 2.50 percent today,
economists predicted in a Bloomberg survey.  The yield on the 5.85 percent debt due March 2021 was 3.95
percent. The baht was at 30.37 per dollar.    China :  China Development Bank  will sell 20 billion yuan ($3
billion) of five-year bonds. The government will also sell 28
billion yuan of three-year debt.  The yield on the government’s 3.77 percent bond due
December 2020 was 3.93 percent, according to Chinabond, the
nation’s biggest debt-clearing house. The yuan was at 6.5684 per
dollar.  Malaysia:  Bank Negara  will sell 500 million ringgit ($164.9
million) of 180-day Islamic notes. The central bank will also
sell a combined 3.5 billion ringgit of 168- and 364-day
conventional bills.  The yield on the 3.835 percent note due August 2015 was
3.50 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0340 per dollar.  Taiwan: The central bank will sell NT$100 billion ($3.4
billion) of 364-day non-deliverable certificates of deposits.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.43
percent. The  Taiwan dollar  was at NT$29.437 per dollar.  India: The government will sell a combined 80 billion rupee
($1.8 billion) of 91- and 364-day bills.  The yield on the benchmark 7.8 percent bond due May 2020
was 7.98 percent. The rupee was at 45.0885 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:  Andrea Wong  in Taipei at 
 awong268@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at   shendry@bloomberg.net  